MINEC
WASTE
DAY_LIGHT
EXIT ABOVE 2179
EXIT NE 3196
EXIT U 3201
ITEM 0 413 ADJ1=259
ITEM 1 611 ADJ1=259 ADJ2=274 VAL2=3201
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 0
The sand is more loose and affords worse footing here than anywhere else you have seen in these wastes, allowing your feet to sink into it up to the ankle in the few moments you spend pausing to look at it.
*DESCRIPTION_END
IFVAR RAC ! 55
	RANDOM DUMMY1 1 10 0
	IFVAR DUMMY1 > 8
		ADD FLAG4 1
		IFVAR FLAG4 = 15
			ECHO OTHERS You notice that %n is beginning to sink into the sand...
		ENDIF
	ENDIF
ENDIF
*DESCRIPTION_START ITEM EXAM 1
The slope is shallow, but even as you look at it, several rivulets of loose sand drift down it from the top of the ridge to add to the shifting piles at your feet. Further north, you see, it only gets worse. Perhaps to the south there will be an easier place to climb...
*DESCRIPTION_END
IFPREVERB UP -1
	CLEARVERB
	IFVAR ROUNDTIME > 0
		STRCVT 0 ROUNDTIME
		ECHO PLAYER [Wait %0 seconds...]
	ENDIF
	IFVAR ROUNDTIME = 0
		IFVAR FLAG3 ! 1
			SKILLCHECK 5 -20 DUMMY2
			IFVAR DUMMY2 >= 0
				DISBAND
				ECHO PLAYER You make your way carefully up the shifting slope... %c[Round: 10 sec]
				EQUAL ROUNDTIME 10
				ECHO OTHERS %N makes %h way carefully up the shifting slope...
				MOVE 3201
				AFFECT 3201
				ECHO OTHERS %N climbs up the loose slope below and onto the top of the ridge.
				POSITION KNEEL
				AFFECT 3197
				RANDOM DUMMY1 1 10 0
				IFVAR DUMMY1 = 2
					ECHO ALL A little sand comes sliding down in %h wake.
				ENDIF
			ENDIF
			IFVAR DUMMY2 < 0
				ECHO PLAYER You begin to climb up the slope, but lose your footing in seconds and slide back down. %c[Round: 5 sec]
				EQUAL ROUNDTIME 5
				ECHO OTHERS %N begins to make %h way up the loose slope but quickly loses %h footing and slides back down.
				POSITION SIT
			ENDIF
		ENDIF
	ENDIF
ENDIF
